{
  "answer": "**Yama Smṛti (unknown-yama-smrti-552f8d) does not prescribe a specific procedure for purification after contact with a corpse.** \n\nIts two chapters focus primarily on penances (*prāyaścitta*) for sins such as killing, forbidden intercourse, eating impure food, and apostasy, as well as punishments (*daṇḍa*) for various offenses.[^1][^2] While it includes a general rule for a twice-born touched by an impure substance (*amedhya*): \"should immediately bathe and touch fire; and at the two twilights, he is always pure,\"[^3] corpses (*śava*) are not explicitly mentioned. Ritual impurity from death (*aśauca* or *sūtaka*) is covered in detail in other Smṛtis like Manu Smṛti or Viṣṇu Smṛti, but not here.\n\n[^1]: Yama Smṛti, Chapter 1, [full chapter](/works/unknown-yama-smrti-552f8d/01/translation/).\n[^2]: Yama Smṛti, Chapter 2, [full chapter](/works/unknown-yama-smrti-552f8d/02/translation/).\n[^3]: Yama Smṛti 1.4A, [paragraph](/works/unknown-yama-smrti-552f8d/01/translation/#p-65c739).",
